Project 8 - NLP¶

Project Description: Twitter US Airline Sentiment¶

Data Description:¶

A sentiment analysis job about the problems of each major U.S. airline. Twitter data was scraped from February of 2015 and contributors were asked to first classify positive, negative, and neutral tweets, followed by categorizing negative reasons (such as "late flight" or "rude service"). Dataset:
The project is from a dataset from Kaggle.
Link to the Kaggle project site: https://www.kaggle.com/crowdflower/twitter-airline-sentiment
The dataset has to be downloaded from the above Kaggle website.

Data Description:¶

The dataset has the following columns: tweet_id; airline_sentiment;airline_sentiment_confidence; negativereason; negativereason_confidence; airline airline_sentiment_gold; name ; negativereason_gold; retweet_count; text; tweet_coord; tweet_created; tweet_location; user_timezone.

Objective:¶

To implement the techniques learnt as a part of the course.

Learning Outcomes:¶

  • Basic understanding of text pre-processing.
  • What to do after text pre-processing: o Bag of words o Tf-idf
  • Build the classification model.
  • Evaluate the Model.

Steps and tasks:¶

  1. Import the libraries, load dataset, print shape of data, data description. (5 Marks)

  2. Understand of data-columns: (5 Marks) a. Drop all other columns except text and airline_sentiment. b. Check the shape of data. c. Print first 5 rows of data.

  3. Text pre-processing: Data preparation. (20 Marks) a. Html tag removal. b. Tokenization. c. Remove the numbers. d. Removal of Special Characters and Punctuations. e. Conversion to lowercase. f. Lemmatize or stemming. g. Join the words in the list to convert back to text string in the dataframe. (So that each row contains the data in text format.) h. Print first 5 rows of data after pre-processing.

  4. Vectorization: (10 Marks) a. Use CountVectorizer. b. Use TfidfVectorizer.

  5. Fit and evaluate model using both type of vectorization. (6+6 Marks)

  6. Summarize your understanding of the application of Various Pre-processing and Vectorization and performance of your model on this dataset. (8 Marks)

Index¶

  • 0. Introduction

  • 1. Read and visualize the dataset & Exploratory data (5 marks)

  • 2. Understand of data-columns: (5 Marks)

  • 3. Text pre-processing: Data preparation. (20 Marks)

  • 4. Vectorization: (10 Marks)

  • 5. Fit and evaluate model using both type of vectorization. (6+6 Marks)

  • 6. Summarize your understanding of the application of Various Pre-processing and Vectorization and performance of your model on this dataset. (8 Marks)

  • 7. CONCLUSIONS

  • 8. APPENDIX

e. Conversion to lowercase.¶

In [102]:
def to_lowercase(words):
    """Convert all characters to lowercase from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = word.lower()
        new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

data2['text'] = data2['text'].apply(lambda x: to_lowercase(x))

In [106]:
def remove_stopwords(words):
    """Remove stop words from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        if word not in stopwords:
            new_words.append(word)
    return new_words 

def lemmatize_list(words):
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
      new_words.append(lemmatizer.lemmatize(word, pos='v'))
    return new_words

def stop_and_lemmat(words): # this function helps to join the words in the variable tex
    words = remove_stopwords(words)
    words = lemmatize_list(words)
    return ' '.join(words)

data2['text'] = data2['text'].apply(lambda x: stop_and_lemmat(x))

I got the following sentence searching on internet reagrding to the doubt: Where to split, before or after the vectorizer.

--This doubt is do to the code in the notebook from the last mentor session --

"First split in train and test set, then fit only on the train set and transform the test set. If you do it the other way around, you are leaking information from the test set to the train set. This might cause overfitting, which will make your model not generalize well to new, unseen data."

6. Summarize your understanding of the application of Various Pre-processing and Vectorization and performance of your model on this dataset. (8 Marks)¶

About Pre-Processing:

  • The Pre-processing was done using variuos techniques and libraries.
  • The pre-processing carried on in this project was done step by step in order to see the result of each command. However, in the real practice it can be much faster making a fuction that compile all the steps and we can run them in 1 go. That will be more efficient.
  • Depending on the number of pre-processing steps we can have different results and that should be tested in the real practice. For instance, the impact of the stopword dictionary and negative words. For this excercice I follow the the dictionary of negative words studied in the lectures but i didn't test the model without the personal dictionary to compare the results. -Adjusting the pre-processing we could try to achieve a higher accuracy of the models. -The final goal of the pre-processing is to have a Text data set clean (with useful information) that we can conver to numbers later on.

Vectorization

After some research I found that the split of the data has to be done before the vectorization, I did it in this way and I was able to use the same X_train for both Vectorization techniques.

  • For this project the pre-processed data was transformed to numbers using 2 vectorization techinques.
  • The idea of converting the text to number (array) is to be ables to generate a dataset readable by the computer.
  • With this vectorized dataset we proceed to feed the models.
  • I got better accuracy result of 78% using countvectorizer, however the difference with TfidfVectorizer is only 2%.
  • I got 1000 columns in the Tfidf in contrast with more than 9000 columns in countVectorizer, which makes the process with Tfidf much faster and maybe with a bigger dataset it is better to work with Tfidf in term of time and money.

Modeling

  • In this project I finally managed the way to test different models more efficiently using loops taken from differents sources on the interenet and the lectures.
  • Random Forest Classifier gives us the best accuracy score, precision scores according to the classification report and using CountVectorizer. -The confusion matrix shows the TP,TN,FP,FN for all the 3 sentiments(negative,neutral and positive),Here also Random Forest Classifier gives better results than the others. -Also it is possible to see that the negative feedback has the highest precision and recall, and that is because the number of negative feedback is also much higher as observed in one of the graphics in the APPENDIX: negative = 9178 // neutral = 3099 // positive =2363. -The number of negative feedbacks is 3 times or more higher than the others which could affect the results as well due to skewnnes. -in 5 of the 6 airlines we can see that the number of negative feedback is much higher than the other, and only the airline "virgind America" has a normal distribution. -The customer service is the most repeated negative feedback (Customer Service Issue =2910 entries) so this could be the 1st issue to be resolved in order to improve the image of the airlines. -The performance of the model could be improved expending more time in the pre-processing and then adjusting hiperparemeters. -For this excercise the hiperparameter were kept as default.

7. CONCLUSIONS¶

  • I was able to create and evalaute different models much faster than in previous project and even make the codes more efficient.
  • I found that many display options and EDA can be done with the data before the pre-processing which will allow us to extract extra information from the data set that can be usefull like for instance: analyse the sentiment for each airline, find the most negative and positive words, look the predominant feedback. By doing this we could suggest in the real practice campain to improve the customer feedback for specific areas.

Last but not least, I discover that NLP techniques has a lot of application and still there is room for improvement and for us to learn. It can be implemented in any are of work and will make comunication with computers and robots much faster and better in the near future

def plot_sub_sentiment(Airline):
    pdf = data[data['airline']==Airline]
    count = pdf['airline_sentiment'].value_counts()
